{{see|Pan|PAN|pan-|Pan-}}
==English==

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/pæn/}}
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-æn|-æn]]

===Etymology 1===
Old English ''[[panne]]'', from West Germanic.  Cognate with Dutch ''[[#Dutch|pan]]'', German ''[[Pfanne]]''.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A wide, flat [[receptacle]] used around the house, especially for cooking.
# The contents of such a dish.
# Strong [[criticism]].

=====Derived terms=====
*[[bedpan]]
*[[flash in the pan]]
*[[frying-pan]]

=====Translations=====
'''flat vessel'''
{{top}}
*Dutch: [[#Dutch|pan]] {{f}}
*Finnish: [[pannu]]
*French: [[poêle]] {{f}}
{{mid}}
*German: [[Pfanne]] {{f}}
*Portuguese: [[caçarola]] {{f}}
*Telugu: [[పెనం]] (penaM)
{{bottom}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|pan|n|ing}}

# {{transitive}} To wash in a pan (of earth, sand etc. when searching for gold).
# {{intransitive}} To turn out (in a specified way); to turn out well.
# {{transitive}} To [[disparage]]; to [[belittle]]; to [[put down]]; to criticise severely.
#: ''The critics really '''panned''' that movie.''

===Etymology 2===
From a clipped form of [[panorama]].

====Verb====
{{en-verb|pan|n|ing}}

# (''transitive & intransitive'') To turn horizontally (of a camera etc.).

=====Derived terms=====
*[[pan and scan]]

